came from Yate (Gloucs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorks Deeds","meanings":["1  Jewish (from Lithuania and Belarus): relationship name from the Yiddish female personal name  <i>Dobke</i>, a pet form of the Old Slavic personal name  <i>Dobre</i>, a derivative of  <i>dobr</i> ‘good, kind’.","2  English: relationship name from a diminutive of the medieval personal name  <i>Dob</i> (  See  Dobb  ). This name seems to have died out by the 1881 census (though  <i>Dobkinson</i> had five bearers there); indeed, some of the following bearers may alternatively belong with (3).","3  English: locative name,  see  Dowbiggin  . Redmonds suggests that Robert Dobkyn, 1383 in   Yorks Deeds   (West Bretton, in Sandal, WR Yorks) is identical with Robert Dowbygyng, a lawyer who held land near Wakefield 1400–16 and was presumably an ancestor of John Dowebygging, 1430 in   Yorks Deeds   (West Bretton, in Sandal, WR Yorks). He also notes the appearance in the Ingleton parish registers of Lawrence Dobbiggin (1627), Elizabeth Dabkin (1633), and Lancelot Dobikin (1652). This form of the name may no longer exist."]},{"name":"Yeatman","meanings":["English (southern): occupational name for a gate-keeper, from Middle English <i>yate</i> + <i>man</i>. Compare   Yates  ."]},{"name":"Gate","meanings":["Anglo-Saxon: Geat, a gate"]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: locative name, probably from Gilderdale (Forest) in Alston (Cumb), as suggested by   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  , rather than from Gildersdale in Warter (ER Yorks), as suggested by   Reaney and Wilson  ."]},{"name":"Yates","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>yates</i> ‘gates’, plural of <i>yate</i>, Old English <i>geat</i> ‘gate’, hence a topographic or occupational name for someone who lived by the gates of a town or castle and who probably acted as the gatekeeper or porter. Compare   Gates  . Alternatively, a variant of the singular form <b>Yate</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Edmond","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Edmund  , now in quite frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Edmond Yate was born about 1400, in Charney Bassett, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Yate, was 42 and his mother, Mrs. William Yate, was 35. He married Margaret de Cornwall. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1465, in Berkshire, England, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1400–1465":"umbes 1400–1465","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1418–1465":"1418–1465","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1435–1499":"1435–1499","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1 July 1435":"1. juuli 1435","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1499":"1499","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","about 1400":"umbes 1400","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1418":"1418","Charney Bassett, Berkshire, England":"Charney Bassett, Berkshire, England","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Charney Basset, Berkshire, England":"Charney Bassett, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1400–1465":"noin 1400–1465","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1418–1465":"1418–1465","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","1435–1499":"1435–1499","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1366–Female"